vectorData.altText: 9. The superior and inferior __________________ arteries are branches of the celiac trunk and superior mesenteric artery, respectively that anastomose at the junction of the foregut and midgut.
That's right! The superior and inferior pancreaticoduodenal arteries together supply blood to the pancreas and duodenum.

The pancreas develops as an outgrowth of the developing duodenum at the dividing line between the foregut and the midgut. The duodenum and pancreas, therefore, receive their blood supply from superior and inferior pancreaticoduodenal arteries, which arise from branches of the celiac trunk and superior mesenteric arteries, respectively.
